                  An object experiencing zero net force is know as a  f_____ object.<br><br>
		  A free object moves with c_________ velocity  <br><br>
		  An free observer is said to be on an i ____  frame.<br><br>

		  <h2>Conceptual questions: </h2>

		  <br><strong>Rules for voting from now on:</strong> Voting is simultaneous (and mostly anonymous)<br><br>
Let's think a bit: Which are good approximation to an inertial frame of reference?

		  <br>
		  <br>
		  <ol  style="line-height:200%" type="A">
		     <!-- longer -->
		     <li>A train coasting at constant speed on a level track.</li>
		     <li> A train rolling down a steep hill with constant acceleration.</li>
		     <li> Your bedroom.</li>
		     <li> All of the above. </li>
			</ol>
		  <br><br>
		  <em>Think-Pair-Share (TPS).</em> Pair and share with your neighbor. Vote after I tell you so.
		  <hr>
		  <hr>
		  <br><br>
<!-- Inertial frame of reference is one moving with constant  -->
<!-- velocity (no acceleration) so answer  is <b> A</b>. -->
 		  First Einstein’s fundamental postulate of special relativity can be stated as:
		  <br>
		  <br>
		  <ol  style="line-height:200%" type="A">
		     <!-- longer -->
			  <li>The form of each physical law is different in all inertial frames.</li>
		     <li> The form of each physical law is the same in all inertial frames</li>
		     <li>Only the form of the laws of mechanics are the same in all inertial frames.  </li>
		     <li> All velocities are relative to the speed of light.</li>
			</ol>
		  <br><br>
		 <hr>
		  <hr>
		 
		  <br><br>

      A light bulb puts out a pulse of light that spreads out
in all directions.  According to Einstein the speed at which the light moves to the right is
<br><br>
		  <ol  style="line-height:200%" type="A">
		     <!-- longer -->
<li> slower for an observer moving to the right than for an 
  observer sitting with the light bulb.</li>		
		     <li> the same speed for both observers.</li>
		    <li> faster for the observer moving to the right than for an
		      observer sitting with the light bulb.  </li>
		   	</ol>
		  <br><br>  <em>Think-Pair-Share (TPS).</em> Pair and share with your neighbor. Vote after I tell you so.
 <hr>
		  <hr>
		 
		  <br><br>

		  How much background do you have in relativity?
		  <br><br>
		  <ol  style="line-height:200%" type="A">
		     <!-- longer -->
		   
		     <li> None </li>
		     <li> I have read popular books and articles on the subject?</li>
		     <li> I have studied it in physics class before.</li>
		     <li> I could be teaching this class</li>
		     <li> I have built a working time machine </li>
		  </ol>
		  <br><br> 
		  <br><br>
		  
<em>Mathematical Descr.iption</em><br>
Notation: $t_0=$ <strong>Propert time</strong> and $\ell_0=$ <strong>Proper lenght</strong>. <br><br>
		    Time Dilation:
		    $$\Delta t=\gamma\, \Delta t_0 $$
		    Length Contraction
		    $$\Delta \ell=\frac{\ell_0}{\gamma}\,.$$

                    <h2>Now lets use it</h2>
                  <p>A muon is created in the atmosphere 3 km above Earth's surface, heading downward at speed $0.98c$. It survives $2.2\mu s$ in its own frame of reference before decaying.<br>
		    (a) If the muon would have not been relativistic, how far would the muon travel before decaying?, and how much longer than $2.2 \mu s$ would it have to survive to reach the surface?<br>
		    <!-- TPS -->
		    <b> Pair up and work on it. </b>
		    <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/iHdviZkM7S4?si=P7COxfkgZMfCxZ-M" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>

		    		  <br><br><br>
		  (b) Relativistically, according to an observer on Earth, how long will the muon survive before decaying? Will it reach the surface?<br>
		  <!-- TPS -->
				  <b> Pair up and work on it</b>.
				  <em>Another new rule:</em> If at some point I think I want your atention, I will raise my hand and once you notice it, please raise your hand as well.
				  <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/iHdviZkM7S4?si=P7COxfkgZMfCxZ-M" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>
		 <br><br><br><br>

		 <b> Poll: </b> Who measures the proper time?
		 <!-- Use printed cards -->
		 <br>(A) Muon 
		 <br>(B) Earthling
    		 <br><br><br><br>

		 <strong>Poll: </strong> According to an Earthling, what's the distance traveled by the muon?
		 <br> (A) $0.98 c\times \Delta t$
		 <br> (B) $0.98 c\times \Delta t_0$
		 <br><!-- Open to the whole class -->
		 Let's revisit item (b), answers? 
 		 
		 <br><br><br><br>
		 (c) Relativistically, according to the muon, what is the dis­tance from the point in the atmosphere where the muon is created to Earth's surface, and how much time will it take this distance to pass the muon?
		 <br>
		 <!-- TPS -->
		 <strong>Pair up and work on it</strong>
		 <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/iHdviZkM7S4?si=P7COxfkgZMfCxZ-M" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>
		 <!-- Use printed cards -->
		 <br><br><br>
		 <strong>Poll: </strong> Considering the distance between the location at which the muon is created and Earth's surface. Does it corresponds to a proper lenght?
		 <br>(A) Yes
		 <br>(B) Not		 
		 <br><br><br><br>
		 <strong>Poll: </strong> According to the muon, how much time will requiere to reach Earth's surface?
		 <br> (A) $\frac{\ell_0}{0.98\, c}$
		 <br> (B) $\frac{\ell}{0.98\, c}$<br><br>
		  </p>
		  <br><br><br><br>
                  <em>Final Clicker</em><br><br>
		  We have seen that from the observer point of view, the muon reach Earth's surface because in Earth's frame the muon survives $11\mu s$, or $8.8\mu s$ more than from muon's reference frame. Suppose the time for available for the muon to reach the surface is slightly smaller than $11 \mu s$, but just enough to still reach the surface. Which of the following is a false statement:
		  <br><br><br>
		  <ol type = "A">
		    <li>The proper time is also smaller. </li>
		    <li>From the muon perspective, it wont reach the surface. </li>
		    <li>The distance traveled by the muon is smaller from the Earth's reference frame. </li>
		    <li>$\gamma$ does not change. </li>
		  </ol>
